description.text:
This is a modification of https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2573484 - I changed the cross-section shape of the wavy parts from rectangles to ellipses. I wanted to strengthen these parts so there would be less movement when printing the upper sections. The change in cross-section helped some, but the results were still not as good as I hoped for. The net result is that the tops of the waves end up being a bit bumpy.

The good news is the spaces between the waves are nice and clean, so that gave me the desired result of nice light patterns when the LED is on. Also, I decreased the tolerance I used for creating STL files, so the curves are much smoother now. And finally, this lamp is about 10% larger than https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2573484. It printed in 33 1/4 hours using a layer height of 0.200 mm and a print speed of 100 mm/sec.

The lamp is designed for an LED "puck" light. Battery operated lights are about $4 each; simply do a web search for "LED puck light" to find several sources. This blog page tells where you can get wall powered lights that are brighter and that work very well: http://birkbinnard.com/blog/wall-powered-led-lights/.

A stencil for airbrushing onto felt sheets to create your own battle mats in 1 inch hex grid. The hexes are roughly 1" center to center in all directions so you can count hexes instead of inches when playing wargames. Also makes deciding facing for rear or side armor when shooting at vehicles flanks easier if you're familiar with how Classic Battletech uses hexes.

Print it, tape some newspaper to the edges to further mask, then airbrush through it onto your felt whatever kind of design you want.

The hex lines are the masked portion so if you use a green felt and airbrush on different shades of green and brown you can have a nice grassy scenic with the original green showing through for the hex outlines or similarly if you do space battles you can airbrush and sprinkle paint for stars and nebula on a black felt and still have the plain black outlines for hex spaces.

description.text:
Just made the original part thicker and added a plate for locking onto the battery, with a couple of slits for holding to belt.

I use this adapter with the TS100 solder iron.

Assembly

Printed both parts in PLA, then:

  1. Fit-check. Hand position both parts on the battery.
  2. Wiring. Used a couple of male blade blue terminals. Potting them in place with epoxi resin.
  3. Gluing. With cyanoacrylate and then filled the gaps with baking soda and cyanoacrylate.

comments.text: I made this.  It was a VeRy tight fit.  The spacing between the side guides is 35 mm apart, but it would fit without filing if it was 37 or 38mm.  Also, the thickness (top to bottom) of the side rails should be 2 or 3 mm less.  I was able to get my print to fit tightly after filing both the top and bottom surfaces of the side rails.  Maybe my 2 battery packs have a "revised" shell compared to  Aguante0's.  I would have remixed it with the improvements, but for some reason, I couldn't get Fusion360 or Tinkercad to manipulate it.  Tinkercad would just shut down as soon as I pointed it to open either of the two parts.

Might require careful rotation and positioning, as well as a minimal (or no) skirt, to fit in a 12x12x12 cm build limit.

NEW EDIT
1) Shortened the bottom perches slightly to easier fit 120x120mm MP Select Mini printer.
2) Extended upper perches. They reach towards the corners of the build area.
3) Added adhesion pads at ends of lower perches to help prevent ABS warping. They are very thin and break off easily after printing.
Note: When using ABS the upper perches will pull away from their supports while printing. The birds love the longer perches and the distorted shape is not noticeable.

Design story

All design done with Tinkercad. First version had holes that were too small for birds to put their heads through. The second version worked well but was weak with thin walls between holes and soon fell apart. The third version had holes that were too big and suet fell out when down to the size of golf balls. Also the walls were too slippery and the birds could not reach the middle position. This version that I am now publishing solves all the problems. The extra perches allow birds to reach all parts of the feeder and the holes are big enough for birds to reach inside but still small enough to prevent suet from falling out until the final crumbs.

title: TronXY X5S - upgraded parts for Gantry and Belt Idlers
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
For the TronXY X5S I have designed some upgrade parts. Mainly to improve the gantry which uses Acrylic parts which flex and break easily, the stock idlers and belt path.

See short video clip:
https://youtu.be/3yFbaJzWN30


The stock belt path is nowhere near parallel and perpendicular where needed, so I designed custom Corner Idler Plates. Added ridges and counter sunk extrusion cur outs to make it more sturdy.

The four wheeled Y carriages have basically one wheel too many, three make a plane. During movement I could see wheels not turning at all due to the forces on the plates. The 3 Wheeler solves that as well. Added ridges and counter sunk extrusion cur outs to make it more sturdy.

[EDIT 1]
If you want to use eccentric nuts for the outer wheels, see the great remix that Joar shared:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2599479



Parts included and needed:

Printed parts (I printed them at 0.28 layer height, 4 top/bottom/perimeters with 80% full Honeycomb Infill):

  • 2x X5S_Y-carriage_3w_ridged_spacers.stl ('3 Wheeler edition' with ridges and integrated wheel spacers)
  • 1x Corner_Idlers_Plate.stl ('as is' for Front Left side)
  • 1x Corner_Idlers_Plate_mirrored.stl (mirrored in XY for Front Right side)
  • 8x M5_holder_608_bearing.stl (when you gonna use them as idlers)
  • 8x 608_bearing_sleeve.stl (when you gonna use them as idlers)


    The following files you can download at SgaboLab, the designer of them. Check out his other great upgrades for the X5S as well!:
    https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2574935/#files

  • 2x spacer A1-spessore-cuscinetto-cinghie-carrelli-8e4mm.stl (under high idlers on Y carriage)
  • 2x spacer C-spessore-torri-cuscinetto-20x8e4.stl (under high idlers on Corner Idler Plates, print them 1mm lowered in Z height --> 7mm high)
  • 1x B2-staffa-cart-estrusore-V2.stl (for X Carriage belt riser)
  • 3x B1-spessore-ruote-ext-6mm.stl (for X Carriage Wheels)

Hardware needed:

  • 8x 608zz bearing (if you do not have 'official idlers' planned already and you gonna use them as idlers)
  • 4x M5x50 screws
  • 3x M5x40 screws
  • 1x M5x35 screws (re-use from kit)
  • 2x M5x30 screws (re-use from kit)
  • 10x M5 washers medium size
  • 12x M5 washers small size (re-use from kit)
  • 4x M4x16 screws
  • 4x M4x9 screws (re-use from kit)
  • 8x M4 washers medium size
  • 12x M4 washers small size (re-use from kit)
  • 8x T-nuts (re-use from kit)

Instructions and parts used:

Y-Carriage:

For assembling the mirrored right side corner idler plate, use your free side cutters to snip off part of the outside ridge where the end stop plate is mounted to make it fit. See photo.

Front Left corner idler plate:

  • high idler: M5x50 screwed into frame,
  • low idler: use the M5x25 from the frame

Front Right corner idler plate:

  • high idler: use a M5x40 (the M5x35 from stock wheel setup is just too short)
  • low idler: M5x50 screwed into frame

Use M4x16 with M4 medium washers and the hammer nuts to mount the plates to the extrusion.


For instructions to assemble the belt riser bracket and X carriage spacers under the wheels, check the Thingy of SgabLab who deisgned them here:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2574935

title: NXP PICO MX7D with touch screen and camera case

description.text:
This is a case for a NXP PICO-PI MX7D kit from Technexion - https://shop.technexion.com/pico-pi-imx7-startkit.html

It is a raspberry pi like board with a touch screen and camera that can run Android Things. The enclosure was designed because I could not find any to 3D print.

The photo is of the first prototype. Some refinements were made, mainly a different mounting for the antenna so that it does not stick out.

Updated v2.00: Modified for a better fit and added some variations with a slot in the bottom for the connector wires and one with holes for 3 square 5x2mm LEDs

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

Prusa Clone

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

15%

Notes:

PLA should be the best option due to low shrinkage. You can use PET as well but ABS is not recommended

You will need 8 x 3mm screws. Length should be about 5-8mm.
Assembly takes some skill, specially mounting the antenna and sliding the board in so be patient.
Start by inserting the antenna cable into the antenna hole. Carefully lower the nut into the hole and tighten the nut with a screw driver through the hole as far as possible. Wedge the nut with a screw driver so that it can not turn and tighten with an 8 mm spanner from the back. Next insert the camera cable and the antenna cable on the NXP board. Fold the camera cable underneath the board and mount the board with 4 screws (these screw heads should be small so that it does not short the tracks.)
Next mount the camera with 2 screws. Insert the screen cables and mount the screen (it might be a tight fit but it should go in unless your plastic shrunk more than mine in which case you might have to enlarge the print by about 0.3-0.7%.)
Last fit the screen. Slide top bezel on from the narrow side of the bezel and press the other side down firmly. Screw it down if you have to but mine fitted snugly enough so that no screws were needed.

This is a M22 size panel mount adapter for standard 15-45A Powerpoles commonly used in amateur radio.
When installed the connector is basically flush with the front of the mounting adapter, I've tested this with connectors with the typical rubber strain relief and there's plenty of clearance.

Thread pitch is 2 mm to simplify printing.

The design includes a screw that holds the Powerpole including clearance for the dovetails ensuring it can only be inserted one way.
The screw includes two flats spaced at 19mm (3/4") to simplify installation.
A matching nut is also included for printing, a 26mm wrench can be used for tightening.

The rear port is large enough to insert the wires after installation if desired.
The Powerpole can either be glued in from the back, or retained using an M2.5 screw through the cross-hole in the screw.

To use the cross-hole you can install a DIN912 style M2.5x10-16 screw and rely on a friction fit.
Optionally you can install a standard M2.5 brass insert (3.8mm outer diameter, 3-4mm length) to better retain the screw, use a M2.5x16 DIN912 screw in that case.

Note: you'll need to be able to print the inner dimensions of the screw to within +-0.1mm, otherwise you may have issues seating the plug. It's designed as a clearance fit so if it's too tight to get in then your print is too small.

In the power supply picture I used 30mm as the hole spacing (center to center), to drill the holes in thin sheet metal a stepped cone drill is a good choice.

Update: 2017-10-14:
I added a v5 DDWG for the screw that includes some additional measurements.

Added a _Rear variant of the screw which allow rear mounting of the powerpole and some other minor changes to chamfering (front is less chamfered and I removed the dovetail-slots from the front).

title: Prusa I3 Rework 1.5 adjustable mount for extruder Z inductive sensor

description.text:
Extrudeur.stl is the file for the modified extruder body.
Chariot.stl is the file for the carriage

This thing is a modification of the Prusa I3 Rework 1.5 extruder.

  • I added a quickly adjustable carriage for the inductive sensor (diameter 12 mm). This way you can fine tune the inductive sensor even when the printer is not connected to the PC with RepetierHost. You don't need to follow the procedure with gcode G92 Z0, G30, M851, M500. Just adjust the wing nut and use auto home in the LCD menu ( better start with a safe setting with inductive sensor below the hot end nozzle and go up gradually screwing the wing nut).
  • It's a bit hardened with two housing for M3.5x16 wood screws. The layers of the first original one I printed splitted by the housing of the M4 nuts. I'm upgrading my Prusa I3 Rework from 1.0 to 1.5 and I hadn't realized yet that the setting of the inductive sensor depends on the temperature of heatbed. When you tune the inductive sensor with heatbed at 55°C, the nozzle will crash into into the heatbed if you use autohome when the heatbed is colder.

I used a cut of about 90 mm of M3 threaded rod with five nuts and a wing nut to attach the carriage on the extruder. I used a spring from my old Wade extruder (Prusa I3 Rework 1.0) but slightly different spring will fit.

For convenience I join F - Extruder_.STL from thing:858449 Prusa i3 Rework 1.5 (licence GPL). (it's imported in the scad files as basis for the modifications).

Quick description of the scad files:

  • M_global.scad: a small general library with shortcuts for translations and rotations and tolerance constant used to ease fittings between pieces printed separately.
  • vis_M3_5_x_16.scad : a library to integrate wood screws size M3.5 x 16 in designs
  • M3.scad : a library to integrate M3 nuts and threaded rods in designs.
  • M6.scad : a library to integrate M6 nuts and threaded rods in designs.
  • interne.scad: the main part of the scad code of the thing. Imports F - Extruder_.STL as basis .
  • Conception.scad : the file used to display in OpenScad a view useful when designing the whole thing (I write the scad files in Lazarus source file editor ).
  • Extrudeur.scad: file used to create Extrudeur.stl, the body of the modified extruder.
  • Chariot.scad: file used to create Chariot.stl, the carriage of the inductive sensor.

Update: for a newer version with better internal wiring using only a 1.6mm /14awg wire, see https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2647700

1 clear plastic circle 26.5mm - you can cut this out of anything, i used a dremel on a demo lens (ask for these at your local optometrist or optical store, they just throw them out)
1 SPST latching switch from junk giveaway flashlights (seen in photo above)
2pc copper (or other metal) strips at least 70mm long

I visit Taco Bell far more frequently than a responsible adult should, and as such, I have a surplus of Taco Bell paper napkins. This design helped me contain the mess that my unused napkins were making. I am not sure how standard napkin sizes are, but Taco Bell napkins are around ~105mm x ~170mm (roughly 4.5x7 inches.

I originally intended the napkins to slide out the bottom, but after printing, I realized there was just too much friction to make that practical. So I re-designed the container to close the bottom to add a little strength. I never ended up printing the lid, but based on my measurements in Blender, there should be plenty room for it to fit over the box.

Now I just need to design a clever way to house the extra hot sauce packets...

The MakerBot Frog Dissection Kit is the first 3D printable curriculum unit for teachers and their students to download and 3D print in the classroom. Now you can teach students about basic anatomy without having to deal with the yuck factor of dissecting a real frog!  
This Frog Dissection Kit includes a lesson plan for teachers, digital files to 3D print a large, life-size frog body, and six 3D printed organs that fit together like puzzle pieces. Download the files, let us know how it prints, and stay tuned for more enriching educational experiences from MakerBot Academy.  
Don't forget to check out the Instructions tab for a sample lesson plan!

Frog Dissection Kit
How does the frog's anatomy relate to its habitat? Grades
6-8 Class periods
3-5

Objectives
Students will understand the following:
  • The importance of frogs in their local ecosystem.
  • Why a frog is uniquely suited to its habitat.
  • Concepts of adaptation and natural selection
    • Students will work in groups to research their frog, acquire background information, conduct student-driven dissections, record their observations, and think critically about the relationship between anatomy and habitat. Students will then communicate what they learned to their classmates with diagrams.

Overview
Students will research their frog and its habitat, dissect the frog, and consider how its anatomy adapted to its environment. They will consider how observations made provide evidence for evolution. Materials

  • One computer with connection to the Internet; one MakerBot Replicator 2 Desktop 3D Printer.

  • Five Frog Dissection Kits (Frog_Body.stl, Organs_Combined.stl)

  • Handouts (Frog_Dissection_Kit.pdf)

  • Paper, pencils, poster boards, markers

Lesson Plan Procedure
This lesson is designed to complement units on human anatomy. A discussion can also be used as a review of human anatomy and to assess what students know about non-human animals. Capturing their curiosity
Curiosity can be captured by introducing the MakerBot 3D printer, showing the 3D print files, and then having the students watch videos of virtual frog dissections online. Student-driven inquiry
Student groups do a student-directed dissection of their 3D printed specimen. Assessment
Students can be assessed by the amount of data they collected about local frog species, the accuracy of their diagrams, and how well they explain their findings to their fellow students.

DAY 1: Introduction

  • Introduce the concept of adaptation and explain how organisms that are best adapted to their environment will have more offspring and over time the population will have more individuals with those beneficial traits. Stress that these changes do not occur on an individual level, but within a population over time. Individuals do not develop changes because they need them, instead, over time, those individuals best suited to the environment have more offspring causing changes in the population. Ask students what they think will happen if the environment changes ÃÂlike another ice age or extreme warming event. Students should be able to predict that populations will have to adapt or go extinct.

  • Introduce the 3D printed frogs.

  • Divide the class into groups and provide each with a model.

  • Within each group, each student picks an organ for which they will be the group expert. This does not mean that the student examines only that organ, just that they will be responsible for explaining that organ to their group and making sure their group members understand its function.

DAY 2: Students research the animals online
  • Have students research frogs online to learn about their habitats and their anatomy. Make sure the students understand that this background knowledge will help them recognize what the structures look like in real life. Discuss with the students the importance of looking at the source of the materials to evaluate the trustworthiness of a site. Diagrams can be printed from these sites.

DAY 3: Dissection

  • Students dissect their frog, identifying organs as they go. Each group should have access to the Frog_Dissection_Kit.pdf to help students identify the organs.

  • As the groups are dissecting, the instructor can walk from group to group, asking what organs they have identified so far. By the end of the class, all students should be able to point out the six major organs.

DAY 4: Diagramming

  • Students examine the specimens they dissected the previous day and diagram the structures in their dissected specimens. Each student is the expertÃÂ on a particular organ and should verify that his/her group-mates have those structures correctly identified. This is a good time to walk around to different tables, observing the diagrams and making sure that the students have correctly identified organs.

  • Each group prepares a poster identifying organ functions and the elements of the frog's habitat.

*DAY 5: Presentations and discussion**

  • Students present their group posters, sharing their findings with the rest of the class.

  • Teacher leads discussion to encourage critical thinking.

*Sample discussion questions

  • Explain the frog's role in the food chain. What would happen to the food chain if frog populations were to decline?

  • Discuss what makes a suitable habitat for a frog. Describe your location and explain why it's a good or poor frog habitat.

  • Currently, frog populations all over the world are in decline. Make hypotheses as to why frog populations are decreasing.

  • A decline in the world's frog populations is often described as an early warning sign for the environment. Debate whether or not this is an accurate statement.

description.text: Fun string lights to show off the RGB functionality of neopixels! The star lights have been created to house Adafruit's Diffused 8 mm Through-Hole LED NeoPixel. However, the LEDs don't need to be neopixels. They can be any type of LED as long as its 8 mm through hole.

Printer:

Creality CR-10

Resolution:

0.2 mm

Infill:

15% or 100%

Notes:

I used glow filament so my stars would glow after being turned off. You can probably use whichever filament you want though I would assume pigmented filament will make the lights dimmer.

As you can see from the pictures, infill does shine through so be sure to choose a nice looking infill (honeycomb, triangle, cat-fill, doughnut-fill) or print at 100%.

Sanding

Caution: There are sharp edges unsuitable for children. Be sure to sand down the points of the star as they are quite sharp.

Getting Started

Neopixels can't light up on their own. They need to be attached to a controller to work. The easiest way to get started is to use an arduino controller.

More about that here: Neopixel Uberguide!

Wiring

Some soldering is required to get everything hooked up. You will probably read up on everything you need to know in the uberguide. However, please look at this pinout explanation so you don't fry your board or your neopixel.

comments.text:
Hi, Please read the summary under thing details. The infill was 12% for the entire print. You simply need to know how many mm's you have of a single color and then using the slicer to tell you how many mm's will be used for that section. If the slicer won't use up all the color in the section you want it to, then simply adjust the infill higher or lower to make it use less or more until it uses all the color for the section you want. You check how much filament is being used in the preview are when you prepare to print. You could then use multi process of varying infill for each section to force it to use up all the color for a section before it changes colors. In my case I used 12% the whole way through because the only color change I wanted to be correct was the green landscape to change where it meets the castle, the rest didn't matter to me. I used S3D as my slicer for this. And no, I didn't have to edit any of the G-code. You can do this with simple math calculations and varying your infill for each level until your desired results are reached. Last thing, how I knew where to change was again simple math. ie... we know this is a 1kg roll that has 4 colors that all repeat one time. That means each color is approx 12% of the roll size which equals 120 grams per solid color leaving 1% for the gradient change between solid colors. That means simply that in this print you must use 120 grams for the landscape before the color change. And your slicer can easily tell you how much filament you'll be using and that's what you are adjusting until satisfied.
By the way this print used just less than half a roll. Somewhere around 400 grams. After the purple color at the top of the castle, the filament would have started over again with green.

description.text:
This is a Mavic Pro Gimbal Anti-Drop Bracket.
It is located on the rear of the Gimbal Dampening Board and it prevent the camera from flopping around too much.

This is NOT the thing you put on your camera for transport that holds it still, it is a part that is necessary for your gimbal to function properly.

I could not find a model file anywhere** so i bought the entire Gimbal Dampening Board, unscrewed this small clip and modeled it in Sketchup.

STL and SKP files available for download, feel free to remix it to your heart's desire.

I made it to precisely the dimensions i got by measuring it with a digital caliper, IE.; i did not put 5mm instead of 4.91mm. If the dimension was 4.91mm, this is what i put in the model.
EXCEPT FOR ONE PART, the top of it was made to 1.5mm instead of 1mm, to help the strenght of the part and because there is enough clearance anyway.

**Oh crap looks like there is a model here already, guess i didn't search well enough.. Oh well. :)
